records.description:
Ever tried getting a sentence translated and then translating it back? That's kind of what I do, minus the translation software.

I take songs that were translated for a Brazilian audience and translate the translation back into English. Since pop songs don't usually get translated, that means the majority of my videos are on songs from children's movies.
Hearing something you're familiar with in the language you're trying to learn is a great way to help familiarize yourself to it.

Keep in mind that sometimes what one says and what is meant can be slightly different. I favour meaning over literal content. I try to point out as many of these differences as I can during the wordless moments in the songs, as well as add any relevant tidbits.

Let me know if you have requests, comments, or questions!

Check me out on Tumblr and Blogger where I talk about Brazilian culture, history, and language.

They're linked near the top of the channel page, all nice and clickable.

records.description:
"Cantonese online" is a channel to learn Cantonese (Yue Chinese) in a chic, easy and fun way!!!

5 facts of CANTONESE :

- It is official language in Hong Kong, Macao and Guangdong.

- It is mainly a tonal (or oral) language.  When it comes to read and write, people use standard traditional Chinese instead. (The same as mandarin users in Taiwan.)

- It is officially defined as one of six leading languages in daily use (not dialect!) by the United Nations. (The six languages are English, Mandarin, Cantonese, Russian, French and Spanish.)
- It has more than 2000-year history. (Mandarin has been around for 700-800 years.)

- It comes from Canton, the former English name of Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong.  However, through years of mass media and pop culture influence, Hong Kong has now truly become the cultural centre of Cantonese.
records.name: Cantonese

records.description:
EnglishZero.com aims to provide a complete course of English language learning for speakers of other languages from beginner level.

The educational materials are designed around Digital Presentation Lessons (DPLs), which are educational slide-show videos with language input, contexts and practice activities. DPLs are designed to be easily accessible from home and mobile digital devices, from large screen TVs and interactive whiteboards, to tablets and smartphones.

DPLs are designed for flexible use; they can be studied by learners remotely, or used by English instructors for learners to study live, in the classroom.

Each DPL has a streaming YouTube video, a downloadable version of the video, the original source, fully editable, PowerPoint .pptx file, and companion worksheets in PDF and editable Word .docx formats.

records.description:
Hello and Bonjour,

Welcome to my channel. I'm Natasha, a native French speaker from Paris who expatriated to England 12 years ago.
I initially created this channel in 2009 because I wanted to share the French songs I grew up listening to with my English speaking friends and had difficulties finding translations online. Culturally, French songs heavily rely on lyrics. It's storytelling. And people who do not speak French hence have issues appreciating the impact of these songs unless they are translated.

I have aimed to keep them as simple as possible, only text, so your own imagination can experience the meaning conveyed by each word/sentence, all rendered in tempo as the song is being played so you can feel its impact as close to how a native speaker might experience it. 

Each video comes with French captions which you can turn on and off at will. Useful for those who which to learn the song or sing along.

If you enjoy them, please subscribe. It encourages me to do more. 

Merci
